        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/34821",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=stefanklug",
                        "name": "stefanklug",
                        "displayName": "Stefan Klug",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi Mario,\n\nI'm sorry, but this is not entirely correct. You're right, that the comparison has to be done with ===. But that's exactly what is done by setting the third parameter of array_search to true.\nSo object referencing should work. But ZF-7634 is still valid. I'll comment on that there...\n\nCheers Stefan",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=stefanklug",
                        "name": "stefanklug",
                        "displayName": "Stefan Klug",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-09-22T13:51:33.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-09-22T13:51:33.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/34825",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=marioklaue",
                        "name": "marioklaue",
                        "displayName": "Mario Klaue",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hi Stefan,\n\nyou are right regarding the === operator. Today I have learned more about the === operator in PHP. It does a comparision based on value and type. I thought it would do a pointer comparision in the sense of C\/C++.  But this is not the case and this is exactly the problem. All objects\/arrays with the same value are treated as identical during AMF serialization. This leads to arkward situations in a Flex client if by accident unrelated object\/arrays have the same value in PHP. \nRegarding ZF-7634, this is really just a special case of a much bigger problem! The problem exists for arbitrary complex arrays and objects. The implemented object referencing mechanism is just to eager. \nI'm working on a solution and i will send a possible bug fix later.\n\nGreetings,\nMario\n ",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=marioklaue",
                        "name": "marioklaue",
                        "displayName": "Mario Klaue",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-09-22T14:46:17.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-09-22T14:46:17.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/34938",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=marioklaue",
                        "name": "marioklaue",
                        "displayName": "Mario Klaue",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Hello,\n\nsorry gays. I'm not able to provide a bug fix which solves the problem for all situations. In my project it was good enough to disable the referencing mechanism for arrays.\nBut I could not find a general solution for the referencing mechanism.\n\nNow I want to believe it is a problem of PHP. If PHP had a function to attach a unique ID to an object  a solution would be easy.\nFor the time being I'm giving up on this problem.\n\nGreetings,\nMario",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=marioklaue",
                        "name": "marioklaue",
                        "displayName": "Mario Klaue",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-09-28T00:33:45.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-09-28T00:33:45.000+0000"
                },
